( ) (The Hon. Deputy Chairman of Committees) Then, the Hon. Rauff Hakeem. You have 11 minutes. [1.39 p.m.] ( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) Hon. Deputy Chairman of Committees, while participating in this important Debate, first, I would like to invite the attention of the Hon. Minister to the financial position of the Sri Lanka Ports Authority. When you look at the income that has been generated by the Sri Lanka Ports Authority - I read from the income report that has been submitted to us - there is a significant improvement compared to the past four years similarly in all the areas. , . , . . 2022 2018 2021 , , . 2022 35 000 , . . [ ] . 2021 2022 , 35 000 , . , . , , . . , , , 2022 35 000 , , . .
( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) Hon. Member, what is the report you are quoting from?
( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) This was given to me by the Parliament Research Division. I will send you a copy of it so that you can reply later.

Having said that, Sir, I would like to deal with the following issues. With the IMF restructuring arrangements, for the first time, the IMF is trying to have a pilot project; they are trying to have a test case with Sri Lanka because they have declared that they will do a

country-specific Governance Diagnostic Review. One of the important elements of that is to look at the corruption vulnerabilities in the affected countries. So, we have, of course, passed an anti-corruption law, but not purely corruption, but inefficiency, which is adding to the burdens of the country, has also to be taken into account.

In fact, at the Meeting of the Committee on Public Finance today - Hon. Minister, your Secretary also came to that - I raised certain issues and particularly, the issue concerning the KKS Harbour. For the KKS Harbour, though some US Dollars 47 million is available from the Indian Credit Line for that, land acquisitions have not been done. For the last four years, that has been dragging on.
( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) Sir, I want to -
( ) (The Hon. Deputy Chairman of Committees) Yes, Hon. Minister? ( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) You can answer, Hon. Minister, when you reply. I have only a limited time.
( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) No, I must reply then and there.

What you said is wrong. The Indian Government has committed US Dollars 45 million for the KKS Harbour. ( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) Sir, you have to deduct this time from the time allotted to him.

( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) Then, we appointed an Indian consultant, to whom we have paid, and he has prepared all the plans. But, the Exim Bank of India has not given concurrence for the project yet.
( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) That is a different matter. The Exim Bank issue is there, I agree. The Exim Bank, with the -

( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) Therefore, with our money, we have put up the buildings et cetera, but for the construction of the breakwater and dredging, we are awaiting for the money, the concurrence from India .

( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) All that is correct, Hon. Minister. But the question is, the Auditor-General, in his Report - I am reading from the Auditor-Generals Report - finds fault with the inefficiency in the acquisition of land for preparing the necessary area for that project. So, those are the issues.

( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) . . rose. ( ) (The Hon. Deputy Chairman of Committees) Yes, Hon. Minister? ( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) Hon. Minister, I will send you the Report. You can reply after looking at the Report.

( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) But, what you say is wrong. ( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) The other thing is regarding the JCT. The Hon. Mahindananda Aluthgamage spoke about the new terminals that are being built - the North and the West Terminals. One is being built by the SLPA itself and the other, by the Adani Group of India. As far as our own JCT is concerned, unless you extend its length beyound the current dimension, that is, the 600-metre length, you cannot handle two vessels with a length beyond 330 metres at the same time. There again, a Cabinet Paper was prepared to extend the length by 120 metres and the draft by 15 metres so that you can have two vessels side by side. Almost Rs. 5,000 million was allocated for that, the Cabinet Paper was passed and the Notice of Commencement of work was to be done within seven days from the date of the contract, but the Notice was issued after a lapse of two years, on the 23rd of November, 2020. Also, it was expected to be completed by 23rd July, 2022. The progress was very slow by last year. I do not know about its situation today.
( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) . . rose.
( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) Hon. Minister, you can reply later. You keep on interjecting. Then, I will not be able to finish my speech.
So, Hon. Minister, you are free to reply to these. These issues have to be looked into and they are inefficiencies in the conduct of affairs.

In the meantime, now, you are seeking to amend the Sri Lanka Ports Authority Act in order to expand the Director Board of the Ports Authority and your justification for that is, the Ministry does not have a representation in it. I myself had been a Minister of Ports Development and Shipping in the past. The Sri Lanka Ports Authority Act gives the Minister extensive powers. That was drafted by the late Hon. Lalith Athulathmudali. So, these attempts to add somebody from the Ministry are all just excuses to have more control in the Board, but that is not going to help you always. The Secretary to the Ministry can always call for review meetings, project review meetings et cetera and can have total control of what is happening in the Sri Lanka Ports Authority.

You do not have to go and sit in the Board of Directors to be guiding it. After all, Hon. Minister, you have the right to appoint five people including the Chairman. Perhaps, what, in fact, you want to do is to have total control of the Board, a majority. That is not the way to go about it. If you want to control the Sri Lanka Ports Authority, you can very well do it with the Secretary calling for review meetings and then supervising the affairs of the Sri Lanka Ports Authority. You have absolute power; this is one of those pieces of legislation where the Minister is vested with so much of power. So, if a conscientious Minister wants to have his way, he need not expand the Board of Directors by having a Ministry representative put there, but certainly, could have all the control without doing it. I do not know, Hon. Minister, for what reason you want the Board expanded, but, anyway, I am just pointing it out for this reason.

Sir, the other matter is with regard to the shipping sector. You have brought in Regulations under the Licensing of Shipping Agents, Freight Forwarders, Non-Vessel Operating Common Carriers and Container Operations Act. 1993 763/8 40 60 , . . This request has been there throughout. You have allowed the shares of this sector to be available for the locals so that foreign companies would not come and take over our shipping

services sector. That is an accepted principle. But, you are giving an excuse for bringing these Regulations, saying that since the Maldives have declared 100 per cent share ownership of their shipping services for their locals, Sri Lankans, who had ownership of those shares earlier, have now been disadvantaged and therefore, in order to teach them a lesson, you are bringing in these Regulations. That is how it had been worded. Therefore, you are putting here, " " . This is the way in which you are trying to prevent that from happening so that you could prevent the Maldivians from coming and owning our shares.

( ) (The Hon. Nimal Siripala de Silva, Attorney-at-Law) Not for those open for Sri Lankans. ( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) Okay. But, you are also putting, " ." Here, you are also having a discretion. The whole purpose, in my opinion, is very superficial. If you are going to have this provision, you are taking by one hand and giving by the other. So, you are retaining the discretion. Retaining such discretion even leads to corruption. So, in my opinion, these things should not happen; you need not have such arrangements because we are now facing a serious problem with the IMF regulations and conditions, particularly, about anti-corruption issues. So, we must not, wherever possible in new legislations, allow the Executive to come and poke their hands into everything. Giving too much of discretion to the Executive on these matters should be prevented; you must limit the discretion. That should be the way to go about, whereas this is the other way about.
( ) (The Hon. Deputy Chairman of Committees) Hon. Member, please wind up now.

( ) (The Hon. Rauff Hakeem, Attorney-at-Law) Yes, I will wind up, Sir, with one particular comment about setting up necessary facilities for landing seacraft. In the list of seacraft landing areas, Arugam Bay is not included. In Arugam Bay, in the past, there had been seaplanes landing. Pottuvil is an important tourist destination. Therefore, Arugam Bay must also be included. Together with that issue, I have also raised the issue of the Batticaloa Airport at the Committee on Public Finance today, to which, Hon.
